AB  - Validated the pilot version of an computer-adaptive testing algorithm for depression (D-CAT) in everyday clinical practice and examined patients' acceptance of computerized test administration. 537 participants (mean age 42 years) suffering from either depressive disorders, somatoform disorders, adjustment disorders/stress reactions, eating disorders, anxiety disorders, dissociative disorders, substance abuse, and unspecified psychiatric disorders completed the D-CAT and rated 10 statements assessing practical, cognitive, and emotional aspects involved in computer-adaptive item administration. German versions of the Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale (HADS), the Center for Epidemiological Studies Depression (CES-D) scale, and the Beck Depression Inventory (BDI) were administered to test convergent validity. A subsample of 114 patients was additionally evaluated using the Composite International Diagnostic Interview (CIDI). Results showed a high overall acceptance of the use of the personal digital assistant and of the mode of item presentation. A predefined reliability of .90 was attained after an average of 6 administered items. Reliable score estimates were possible with 10 or fewer items in 95% of cases. Moreover, convergent validity ranged from r=.68 to r=.77. The D-CAT discriminated between diagnostic groups as well as the other measures did. The D-CAT is considered a short and precise measure of depressive symptoms.
