AB  - Examined the sensitivity and reliability of computerized adaptive testing (CAT) for the assessment of self-reported anxiety and depression outcomes compared to standard static clinical monitoring instruments. Based on item response theory, CATs are designed to minimize response burden while maximizing measurement precision. Longitudinal data collected for 595 psychosomatic inpatients were reanalyzed with correlation and ANOVA statistics for the purpose of examining three specific CATs' retest reliability and sensitivity to change compared to the Generalized Anxiety Disorder 7-item scale, the Patient Health Quesionnaire-9, and the Patient Satisfaction Questionnaire. The three CATs have been used in daily clinical routines for more than a decade. The results showed that all three caused low patient burden. They also administered, on average, 5-7 items with similar retest reliability compared to their corresponding static tools. All three CATs also proved to be as sensitive to change as their corresponding static tools. Future research will include multicenter assessments, external clinical criteria, multidimensional CATs, content balancing, and theta-dependent stopping rules.
